    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-03-21T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-03-21T08:00:00-05:00" n="385"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d385">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">368.1121 Stephano, Christopher/6: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-21T15:00:00+02:00"
                            >March 21, 1935—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 21—2 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>42. Department’s 12, March 11, 7 p.m. Christopher Stephano is still under
                    detention and I am confidentially informed that he is accused by the military
                    authorities of high treason. This seems to show that these authorities are not
                    taking into consideration his American citizenship.</p>
                <p>According to the Legation’s understanding Christopher was born subsequent to the
                    naturalization of his father Stephen which took place prior to 1914. If this is
                    true he is recognized by Greek law as an <pb facs="0575" n="499" xml:id="pg_499"
                    /> American citizen. Please inform me of date and court of naturalization of
                    father and date and place of birth of son.</p>
                <p>I believe that the time has now come to make immediate formal inquiry of the
                    Greek Government as to the charges against this citizen. On account of the
                    existence of martial law, informal steps seem unlikely to secure prompt military
                    answer. Please instruct.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
